title: For Sale:  1864 SPRINGFIELD Allin Conversion Model TRAPDOOR
postcontent: As the US Civil War drew to a close, it was quite apparent to everyone that muzzleloading rifles were obsolete, and any military force wishing to remain relevant would need to adopt cartridge-firing weapons. However, the Union arsenals had a million or more muzzleloading rifled muskets still on hand. How to modernize the weaponry without simply throwing away all those existing guns? The task was put to Springfield Arsenal master armorer Erskine Allin in 1864, and he devised a “trapdoor” style of conversion to turn an old Springfield muzzleloader into a breechloader. He had the benefit of having seen the previous year’s extensive trials of breechloaders, but the final product was his combination of what he judged to be the best elements of the ideas available. The result has long been known colloquially as the Trapdoor Springfield, and this 1864 model was the very first of them. It was still in .58 caliber, and used a rather complex extractor system. It would soon be revised to make improvements to it, and ultimately a .45-70 model became standard for US infantry and cavalry forces – and remained their standard until the adoption of the Krag-Jorgensen in the 1890s. 3% Surcharge on all Credit Card TransactionsNO CALIFORNIA SALES!

title: For Sale:  Springfield 1903 30-06 Stk #A310
postcontent: This is an original Springfield 1903 chambered for 30-06. It is believed to be built in 1918 and refurbished at the Philippine Ordnance Depot in 1928. It has a 24” blued barrel in good condition. The barrel is marked “SA / 9-28” behind the standard blade front sight. The bore is rough but still has it’s rifling. The barrel band (marked “U”) and bayonet lug (marked “H”) are also in good condition with no pitting or dents.  The rear sight has been removed. The receiver is in decent condition. The finish is even and undamaged by scratches or corrosion, but it has been drilled and tapped for a peep sight. The bolt is developing a patina and is also undamaged by corrosion. “C14” is stamped under the bolt handle. The stock reinforcing bolt is missing. The walnut stock is also in fair condition. There are dents and scratches throughout but no cut marks. A notch has been cut out of the right side under the part of the receiver that was drilled and tapped. There are two “P” cartouches behind the trigger guard, one circled, one uncircled. The stock has two overlapping cartouches on the left side above the trigger guard; “POD” in a box and “AWL” in an open box. Stock has two sling swivels, a stacking swivel, and a buttplate with a trap. Comes with original 1943 sling. Length of pull is 13”, overall length is 43-½”, and weight is 8.8 lbs. Our stock number is #A310. Willing to ship anywhere in the US to your FFL, buyer pays freight and insurance.

title: For Sale:  Tokarev SVT- 40 7.62x54R "Soviet M1 Garand"
postcontent:
The SVT-40 saw widespread service during and after World War II. Intended to be the new service rifle of the Soviet Red Army production was disrupted by the German invasion in 1941 resulting in a switch back to the older Mosin-Nagant bolt-action rifle for the duration of WWII. After the war new rifles were adopted by the Soviet, SKS and AK-47.
Developed from the earlier SVT-38, the SVT-40 became available to re-equip some Soviet units just in time for the German invasion.The increased firepower of these formations came as an unpleasant surprise for the invaders. It has been called the "Soviet M1 Garand" because it was to be the new battle rifle for the Soviets to replace the aging Mosin-Nagant.
